#compdef voc
# =============================================================================
# voc — Vishap Oberon Compiler — a free, open-source compiler for
#       Niklaus Wirth + H. Mössenböck's OBERON-2 programming
#       language.  Vishap (Armenian for "dragon") is the family
#       of compilers and runtime maintained by Norayr Chilingarian
#       (Armenian software engineer) + David C. W. Brown +
#       contributors, descended from Josef Templ's original
#       OFRONT compiler (the Software Templ OEG / TU Vienna
#       Oberon-to-C source translator from the late 1990s).
#       voc COMPILES OBERON-2 SOURCE TO C, then automatically
#       invokes a host C compiler (gcc/clang/msvc) to produce
#       native binaries.  Distinctive properties of voc:
#         - Self-hosting: the compiler itself is written in
#           Oberon-2 and bootstraps via committed C-source
#           snapshots in `bootstrap/`
#         - Supports THREE distinct size models for elementary
#           types (-O2 Oberon-2 / -OC Component Pascal / -OV
#           alternate large model)
#         - Supports THREE distinct address-size + alignment
#           targets (-A44 32-bit, -A48 32-bit Windows, -A88
#           64-bit)
#         - VT100-styled colored status output (disable with -f)
#         - Per-file option scoping: options BEFORE the first
#           filename apply globally; options AFTER a filename
#           apply only to that file (rare per-positional-arg
#           option semantics)
#         - Repeated options TOGGLE — `-r -r` first enables
#           range checks then disables them
#         - Halt-on-error runtime safety: pointer-init, assertion,
#           range, type-guard, index checks all controllable
#           via individual flags
#
# Author:  Vishap Oberon Compiler — Norayr Chilingarian
#          (Yerevan, Armenia — founder antranigv.am and Vishap
#          UCO/Universal Compiler Operations) + David C. W. Brown
#          (UK; lead recent maintainer 2015-present) +
#          contributors.  Descended from Josef Templ's OFRONT
#          (Software Templ OEG / TU Vienna, late 1990s) — the
#          original Oberon-to-C translator from which all
#          vishap-lineage compilers (vov, voc, OBERON-07) derive.
# Source:  https://github.com/vishapoberon/compiler
#          https://vishap.oberon.am/
# CLI:     src/compiler/OPM.Mod — `ScanOptions` procedure
#          implements a CASE-on-character ladder over each
#          option string.  Argv access is via Oberon stdlib's
#          `Modules.GetArg(VAR pos: INTEGER; VAR s: ARRAY OF CHAR)`
#          and `Modules.ArgCount` — the Oberon module-system
#          run-time exposes process argv as a 1-indexed sequence
#          of strings.  Help text generation is hand-rolled in
#          `OpenPar` procedure via LogWStr calls.
# Library: Oberon Modules.GetArg (vishap runtime) + ScanOptions
#          CASE-character ladder
#          ("Modules" is the Oberon-2 runtime module that exposes
#           the program's argv via 1-indexed GetArg.  ScanOptions
#           in OPM.Mod is voc's hand-rolled argv interpretation:
#           a CASE statement over each character of each option
#           string, with side-effecting `Options := Options /
#           {bitname}` toggles via Oberon's symmetric-set-
#           difference operator.)
