# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 75TH LANGUAGE
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy welcomes
# its 75TH DOCUMENTED LANGUAGE — OBERON-2 (Niklaus Wirth + H. Mössenböck,
# 1991; voc-flavored Oberon-2 by Templ → Norayr/Brown 1997-present) —
# and its FIRST documented Oberon-family CLI mechanism: the Oberon
# stdlib's `Modules.GetArg`/`Modules.ArgCount` combined with hand-rolled
# `ScanOptions` CASE-character ladder using Oberon's symmetric set-
# difference operator for option-bit toggling.
# Taxonomy now spans 308 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 75 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R566 Rust=49 color-eyre → R567 Go=49 kingpin →
# R568 TS-Node=49 parseArgs) followed by 1 NEW LANGUAGE (R569 Oberon-2
# THIS).  Leaderboard unchanged: Rust=49, Go=49, TypeScript-Node=49
# (three-way tie since R568).
#
# Oberon-2 is DISTINCT from every other documented language by being
# a MINIMALIST WIRTH-TRADITION SUCCESSOR — the third major language
# in the Pascal → Modula-2 → Oberon → Oberon-2 lineage by Niklaus
# Wirth (Pascal 1970 / Modula-2 1978 / Oberon 1987 / Oberon-2 1991 /
# Oberon-07 2007).  Each Wirth language SHRINKS the previous: Oberon
# is smaller than Modula-2 (no separate definition modules, no
# nested procedures with reduced rules), and Oberon-2 only adds two
# things to Oberon — TYPE-BOUND PROCEDURES (methods) and READ-ONLY
# EXPORTS.  This adherence to MINIMALISM is the Wirth signature.
#
# The taxonomy now documents the Wirth lineage with TWO entries:
#   - Modula-2 (R??? via MOCKA _mocka — Karlsruhe Modula-2 compiler)
#   - Oberon-2 (R569 THIS via voc — Vishap Oberon Compiler)
# Pascal is undocumented (no Free Pascal/GNU Pascal completion with
# taxonomy header in corpus); Oberon-07 (the 2007 minimalist revision)
# would be a future addition via OBNC (Oberon-Berkeley Native Compiler
# by Karl Landström).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS OBERON-2 AND WHY IS IT THE 75TH LANGUAGE?
#
# Oberon-2 is a minimalist programming language designed by Niklaus
# Wirth + Hanspeter Mössenböck in 1991 at ETH Zurich.  Oberon-2's
# distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ALL THE OBERON-1 FEATURES + TYPE-BOUND PROCEDURES + READ-ONLY
#      EXPORTS — Oberon-1 (1987) was Wirth's response to the
#      complexity creep of Modula-2.  Oberon-1 stripped Modula-2's
#      separate definition modules, enumeration types, FOR-loops
#      (replaced by WHILE), and many other features down to a
#      minimal core.  Oberon-2 (1991) added back EXACTLY TWO things:
#         * TYPE-BOUND PROCEDURES (methods): A procedure can be
#           declared with a receiver parameter that binds it to a
#           specific record type, allowing method-style call syntax.
#         * READ-ONLY EXPORTS: An identifier can be exported with
#           `-` (export suffix) to make it visible but not assignable
#           from importing modules.
#      No other changes — Oberon-2 is literally Oberon plus two
#      orthogonal features.  This is the most surgical language
#      revision in the Wirth lineage.
#
#   2. CASE-SENSITIVE KEYWORDS IN UPPER CASE — All Oberon-2
#      keywords are uppercase: MODULE, BEGIN, END, PROCEDURE, VAR,
#      CONST, TYPE, IMPORT, IF/THEN/ELSE/ELSIF, WHILE, REPEAT,
#      LOOP, FOR (added back in Oberon-2!), RECORD, ARRAY, POINTER,
#      etc.  Identifiers are case-sensitive (distinct from Pascal/
#      Modula-2's case-insensitive).  This makes Oberon-2 code
#      visually distinctive — the keywords stand out from
#      identifiers.
#
#   3. MODULES + MODULE BODIES AS INITIALIZATION — Every Oberon-2
#      compilation unit is a MODULE with a name, IMPORT list,
#      declarations, and an optional MODULE BODY (the statement
#      sequence between BEGIN and END inside the module).  The
#      module body is executed exactly once at program startup,
#      after all imported modules have been initialized.  This
#      is Oberon's approach to "the main program" — instead of a
#      special `main()` function, the program is the module body
#      of the LAST module to be initialized.
#
#   4. GARBAGE COLLECTION — Oberon-2 (and the original Oberon)
#      use garbage collection for heap-allocated POINTER TO RECORD
#      values.  Wirth integrated GC into the language because the
#      Oberon System (the OS Wirth was building) required automatic
#      memory management to be reliable.  This made Oberon-family
#      languages among the FIRST mainstream systems languages with
#      built-in GC (along with Modula-3).
#
#   5. NO SEPARATE DEFINITION + IMPLEMENTATION MODULES — Where
#      Modula-2 has separate DEFINITION MODULE and IMPLEMENTATION
#      MODULE files (.def and .mod), Oberon-2 has a SINGLE MODULE
#      file (.Mod or .mod).  Exports are marked inline with a `*`
#      suffix on the identifier (`PROCEDURE Foo*(...)` makes Foo
#      visible to other modules).  Read-only exports use `-`.
#      Compare:
#         * C/C++: separate .h and .c files
#         * Pascal: optional separation via UNIT INTERFACE/IMPLEMENTATION
#         * Modula-2: REQUIRED separate .def and .mod files
#         * Oberon-2: single .Mod file with * and - export suffixes
#      FIRST documented language in the taxonomy with explicit
#      per-identifier-suffix export-visibility marks (vs separate
#      definition files, vs interface sections, vs explicit
#      `export` statements).
#
#   6. THE OBERON SYSTEM — Oberon-2 was designed alongside an
#      operating system (the Oberon System, originally on Ceres
#      workstations at ETH Zurich) where the OS itself was written
#      entirely in Oberon-2.  The Oberon System pioneered:
#         * Single-user interactive workstation OS in a high-level
#           language with GC
#         * Texts-as-active-documents (every word in the user
#           interface is a clickable command — the "ETOS" model)
#         * Dynamic module loading + unloading at the OS level
#      Modern descendants: A2 / Bluebottle / Active Oberon (active
#      research projects from ETH Zurich), Oberon System V5
#      (community port for modern hardware).
#
# Use cases for Oberon-2:
#   * Teaching minimalist language design (Wirth used Oberon in
#     compilers + OS courses at ETH for decades)
#   * Educational compilers + interpreter exercises
#   * Embedded systems (Astrobe is an Oberon-07 compiler for
#     ARM Cortex-M; voc and OBNC for native binaries)
#   * Research in module systems, GC, structural type extension
#   * Bootstrapping demonstrations (voc bootstraps from Templ-
#     era committed C sources in `bootstrap/`)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE voc CLI — Modules.GetArg + ScanOptions CASE-character ladder
#
# voc's argv parsing is in src/compiler/OPM.Mod, ScanOptions
# procedure.  The structure:
#
#     PROCEDURE OpenPar*(): BOOLEAN;
#       VAR s: ARRAY 256 OF CHAR;
#     BEGIN
#       IF Modules.ArgCount = 1 THEN
#         (* Print usage and return FALSE *)
#       ELSE
#         (* Set defaults *)
#         Options := {inxchk, typchk, ptrinit, assert};
#
#         (* Pick up global option changes from start of command line *)
#         S := 1; s := "";  Modules.GetArg(S, s);
#         WHILE s[0] = OptionChar DO     (* '-' *)
#           ScanOptions(s);
#           INC(S); s := "";  Modules.GetArg(S, s)
#         END;
#         (* ...then per-file loop... *)
#       END
#     END OpenPar;
#
#     PROCEDURE ScanOptions(VAR s: ARRAY OF CHAR);
#       VAR i: INTEGER;
#     BEGIN
#       i := 1;  (* skip the '-' *)
#       WHILE s[i] # 0X DO
#         CASE s[i] OF
#         | "p": Options := Options / {ptrinit}
#         | "a": Options := Options / {assert}
#         | "r": Options := Options / {ranchk}
#         | "t": Options := Options / {typchk}
#         | "x": Options := Options / {inxchk}
#         | "e": Options := Options / {extsf}
#         | "s": Options := Options / {newsf}
#         | "F": Options := Options / {forcenewsym}
#         | "m": Options := Options / {mainprog}
#         | "M": Options := Options / {mainlinkstat}
#         | "S": Options := Options / {dontasm}
#         | "c": Options := Options / {dontlink}
#         | "f": Options := Options / {notcoloroutput}
#         | "V": Options := Options / {verbose}
#         | "O": (* requires one following character: 2 | C | V *)
#         | "A": (* requires two following digits: AddressSize Alignment *)
#         ELSE LogWStr("warning: option ignored")
#         END;
#         INC(i)
#       END
#     END ScanOptions;
#
# Notable about this scheme:
#
#   1. SET-SYMMETRIC-DIFFERENCE TOGGLE — Each option flips a bit
#      in the `Options` SET via `Options := Options / {bitname}`.
#      Oberon's `/` operator on SET values is SYMMETRIC SET
#      DIFFERENCE (XOR).  So passing the same option twice
#      TOGGLES it.  `voc -r -r file.mod` first enables then
#      disables range checking.  Documentation says: "Repeating
#      an option toggles its value."  FIRST documented argv
#      parser with set-symmetric-difference toggle semantics.
#
#   2. PER-FILE OPTION SCOPING — Options appearing BEFORE the
#      first filename apply globally to all subsequent files.
#      Options appearing AFTER a filename apply only to the
#      next file.  Example: `voc -s alpha.mod beta.mod main.mod
#      -m` — `-s` applies globally; `-m` applies only to
#      main.mod.  FIRST documented argv parser with per-
#      positional-argument option scoping (vs strictly global
#      options).
#
#   3. CHARACTER-CASE LADDER PARSING — Each option string is
#      parsed character by character via Oberon's CASE statement.
#      Multiple single-character options can be combined into
#      one argv string: `voc -sm file.mod` is equivalent to
#      `voc -s -m file.mod`.  Compare:
#         * GNU getopt: `getopt_long` parses combined single-
#                        char flags similarly
#         * Plan 9 ARG(2): similar character-by-character
#         * Oberon ScanOptions: CASE-statement-on-CHAR ladder
#                                with no library; pure language
#                                construct
#      FIRST documented argv parser using Oberon's CASE statement
#      on character values.
#
#   4. RUNTIME-LEVEL ARGV ACCESS VIA Modules — Oberon's `Modules`
#      runtime module exposes argv via `Modules.ArgCount`
#      (integer) + `Modules.GetArg(VAR pos: INTEGER; VAR s:
#      ARRAY OF CHAR)` — the user must allocate a fixed-size
#      character array and pass it by VAR; Modules.GetArg copies
#      argv[pos] into it.  1-indexed (consistent with C's argv
#      where index 0 is the program name and 1+ are user args,
#      but Oberon uses index 1 = first user arg, not program
#      name).  FIRST documented argv access via fixed-size
#      character-array out-parameter (vs return-value-string).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented CLI parser:
#
#   1. SET-SYMMETRIC-DIFFERENCE TOGGLE — Every other documented
#      argv parser treats repeated flags as IDEMPOTENT (second
#      occurrence is silently overwritten).  voc's `Options :=
#      Options / {bit}` TOGGLES the bit, so `-r -r` cancels.
#
#   2. PER-FILE OPTION SCOPING — Every other documented argv
#      parser collects flags globally (or per-subcommand).
#      voc applies options per-file based on argv position
#      relative to filenames.
#
#   3. SINGLE-CHARACTER CASE-STATEMENT PARSING — Every other
#      documented argv parser uses string equality or hash
#      lookup on flag names.  voc uses Oberon's CASE statement
#      on a single CHAR.
#
#   4. STDLIB-MODULES.GetArg INTERFACE — Every other documented
#      argv access mechanism returns string values directly.
#      voc's Modules.GetArg requires the caller to provide a
#      VAR ARRAY OF CHAR for output.
#
#   5. ALL FLAGS DEFAULT TO ENABLED-OR-DISABLED INTERPRETATIONS
#      VARYING — In voc, flags `-p -a -t -x` are ON by default
#      and flags `-r -e -s -F -m -M -S -c -f -V` are OFF by
#      default.  Since repeating a flag TOGGLES, this means
#      passing `-p` actually DISABLES pointer-init.  Documented
#      explicitly: "All options are off by default, except where
#      noted above."  FIRST documented argv parser with mixed
#      default-enabled-or-disabled toggle semantics.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/vishapoberon/compiler/blob/master/src/compiler/OPM.Mod
# ScanOptions procedure CASE branches + OpenPar usage text.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '-p[toggle pointer-init-to-NIL safety check (default ON)]' \
    '-a[toggle assertion-failure halt (default ON)]' \
    '-r[toggle range-check failure halt (default OFF)]' \
    '-t[toggle type-guard failure halt (default ON)]' \
    '-x[toggle index-out-of-range halt (default ON)]' \
    '-e[allow extension of old symbol file]' \
    '-s[allow generation of new symbol file]' \
    '-F[force generation of new symbol file]' \
    '-m[this module is main; link dynamically]' \
    '-M[this module is main; link statically]' \
    '-S[do not call C compiler]' \
    '-c[do not link]' \
    '-f[disable VT100 control chars in status output]' \
    '-V[verbose: display compiler debugging messages]' \
    '-O2[size model: 8/16/32-bit Oberon-2 elementary types]' \
    '-OC[size model: 16/32/32/64-bit Component Pascal types]' \
    '-OV[size model: 8/32/64-bit alternate large model]' \
    '-A44[target: 32-bit addresses, 32-bit alignment (Linux/x86)]' \
    '-A48[target: 32-bit addresses, 64-bit alignment (Windows/x86, Linux/ARM)]' \
    '-A88[target: 64-bit addresses, 64-bit alignment (all 64-bit platforms)]' \
    '*:Oberon-2 source file:_files -g "*.(mod|Mod|MOD)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
